  "editorial": {
    "headline": "Jazz Chisholm Jr. Powers Yankees Past Red Sox with Late Blast",
    "subheadline": "New York Yankees beats Boston Red Sox.",
    "lead_angle": "Yankee Stadium erupted in the eighth inning when Jazz Chisholm Jr. lined a three-run home run into the right-field seats, lifting the New York Yankees to a 6-1 victory over the Boston Red Sox. Reliever Tim Hill secured the win with a clean frame out of the bullpen, while Boston reliever Justin Slaten took the loss after failing to escape the late-inning jam.\n\nA quiet afternoon suddenly shifted in the bottom of the eighth inning. With the score locked in a 1-1 tie, Slaten struggled with his command, putting two runners aboard with a quick walk and a hit batsman. Chisholm then hammered a hanging slider deep into the seats to break the tie, followed immediately by Cody Bellinger smashing a solo shot to right. Trent Grisham capped the five-run surge with a sharp run-scoring single to center.\n\nGrisham proved to be the day's toughest out, finishing 3-for-4 with an RBI, while Chisholm ended the afternoon 1-for-4 with three runs driven in on his pivotal blast. This high-stakes division matchup carries immense weight in the American League East standings as the summer heat begins to shape the wild-card chase. Taking this rivalry game gives New York vital momentum and a critical edge in the postseason race.",
